INSERT INTO `gxd_posts` VALUES("223", "1", "2015-11-02 22:15:33", "2015-11-02 22:15:33", "<span style=\"color: #ddb305;\">LEARN ABOUT EBOLA</span>\r\nSierra Leone is at the epicenter of the worst Ebola epidemic on record. The 5,300 cases of Ebola documented by December of 2014 in Sierra Leone alone are more than twice the total number of cases in all other 30 outbreaks combined. Sierra Leone is one of the three countries, along with Guinea and Liberia, bearing the brunt of the epidemic.\r\nEbola virus disease (EVD) causes acute, often fatal, hemorrhagic fever in humans and other primates. It was first identified in what is now the Democratic Republic of the Congo near the Ebola River in 1976.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ddb305;\">Current Ebola Outbreak</span>\r\nAccounts for eighty-five percent (85%) of all cases of Ebola ever diagnosed and seventy-five percent (75%) of Ebola deaths over all known outbreaks.\r\nIs the first large outbreak in this area of West Africa.\r\nIs the first time eight countries have been involved in an outbreak. Previous outbreaks reached a maximum of three countries.\r\nIs the most geographically widespread outbreak of Ebola.\r\nIs the first time cases have been seen in large cities, including Freetown.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ddb305;\">About Ebola</span>\r\nThere is currently no cure for Ebola.\r\nEbola can be 90% fatal if left untreated.\r\nThe death rate can be reduced to less than 50% through supportive medical measures.\r\nEbola can incubate for up to three weeks before symptoms are exhibited.\r\nPatients become contagious when they begin showing symptoms.\r\nEbola occurs primarily in remote, tropical areas in Central and West Africa.\r\nHuman trials of Ebola vaccine have begun, but the results will not be known for several months.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ddb305;\">Ebola Symptoms</span>\r\nThe first symptoms of Ebola are flu-like: headache, fever, joint and muscle aches, sore throat and weakness.\r\nThe acute phase of the disease is characterized by: internal and external bleeding, diarrhea, vomiting, stomach pain, red eyes and rash.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ddb305;\">How Ebola is Spread</span>\r\nThe Ebola virus is spread through direct contact with blood or other secretions from an infected person or animal.\r\nReuse of needles.\r\nSomeone exposed to Ebola may travel long distances before displaying symptoms.\r\nFuneral practices which involve contact with the deceased.\r\nPeople can remain contagious for seven weeks after recovering from Ebola.\r\nApes, monkeys, bats, forest antelope, and porcupines have all been found to carry Ebola.\r\nPreparation and consumption of bush meat (wild animals).\r\nLeonean staples include rice, oil, onion, salt and maggie—a popular seasoning blend.", "Ebola", "", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "27-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-11-02 22:15:33", "2015-11-02 22:15:33", "", "27", "http://ideafoundation.tk/27-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
